  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Keil and Delitzsch Biblical Commentary on the Old Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "(Heb.: 21:14) After the song has spread abroad its wings in twice three tetrastichs, it closes by, as it were, soaring aloft and thus losing itself in a distich. It is a cry to God for victory in battle, on behalf of the king. \"Be Thou exalted,\" i.e., manifest Thyself in Thy supernal (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 57:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", 12) and judicial (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Psalm 7:7",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".) sovereignty. What these closing words long to see realised is that Jahve should reveal for world-wide conquest this גּבוּרה, to which everything that opposes Him must yield, and it is for this they promise beforehand a joyous gratitude. ",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
